snippet.textDisplay: I would love to tell you my most important games from this decade. But unfortunately, I did not play that many games this decade.
snippet.textOriginal: I would love to tell you my most important games from this decade. But unfortunately, I did not play that many games this decade.

snippet.textDisplay:
Minecraft is the ultimate indie game, strong for a full 9 Years and counting.
Super smash bros as a series started in 1999, but in the past decade, they have listened to what fans wanted in the game, while it was being sold as DLC, it shows the value of what actually listening to fans can bring. It is too a point that a single Mii skin, not even a full character, gained so much notoriety that is broke the internet for a bit.
Legend of Zelda: breath of the wild and God of War (2018) were beautiful games, expansive, and filled with mystery, they showed that putting heart in a game could produce something well worth the payoff.
Star citizen encapsulates what crowd funding can accomplish, while admittedly it is basically pay to win as is, it's universe is massive, with an attention to detail that very few games have bothered having to date.
GTA V, while outdated now, showed that spending massively to produce a game can pay off.
Resident Evil 7 While being alright on it's own, it's VR support produced something grand, and really assisted in showing VR as something worth investing in.

snippet.textDisplay:
I would also like to make the case that words with friends made a huge impact for certain people as well. I know it’s in the casual game category, and I myself don’t play the game, but allow me to explain:
Whenever my mom tried to call me and my brother while we played an online game, we to explain to her that we were going against real people in real time, so there was no way to pause the game, but she never really got the message and kept calling us. But then one day, I asked my mom to help me with something, and saw that she was playing this new words with friends battle thing. (Basically, two teams of five have to spell enough words until one of the teams gets 700 points.) Of course, I didn’t press her to hurry cause I knew what it was like to be on an online match, but while she was playing I pointed out that this was basically how my brother and I felt when she tried to call us during a game that couldn’t be paused, and ever since then she’s been way better with online games now that she’s had a taste for it herself.
snippet.textOriginal:
I would also like to make the case that words with friends made a huge impact for certain people as well. I know it’s in the casual game category, and I myself don’t play the game, but allow me to explain:
Whenever my mom tried to call me and my brother while we played an online game, we to explain to her that we were going against real people in real time, so there was *no way to pause the game,* but she never really got the message and kept calling us. But then one day, I asked my mom to help me with something, and saw that she was playing this new words with friends battle thing. (Basically, two teams of five have to spell enough words until one of the teams gets 700 points.) Of course, I didn’t press her to hurry cause I knew what it was like to be on an online match, but while she was playing I pointed out that this was basically how my brother and I felt when she tried to call us during a game that couldn’t be paused, and ever since then she’s been way better with online games now that she’s had a taste for it herself.

snippet.textDisplay: GTA 5 and Garry’s Mod? No where? I’ve never played GMod but I’ve watched days worth of gameplay of it or weeks worth. It arguably is THE game that best embodies the last decade (other than Minecraft). YT gaming was built on Minecraft, GMod, and Call of Duty, but a lot of the biggest channels on YT were built on the back of GMod. Vanoss, Wildcat, H2O Delirious, SeaNanners, EatMyDiction, Gassy Mexican, Chilled Chaos among many other ditched CoD for it and their channels soared. It also had huge creation tools. It allowed fans to create and collaborate with creators. It was far more impactful than Mario Maker. GTA 5 is the most profitable game ever (unless Fortnite has passed it). People are still watching this game after 6 years, let alone playing it. It, like GMod, had creation tools that led to an infinite number of crazy maps, tracks, and game modes. Both were more impactful than every game you listed.
